        Why Schengen Calculators Give Different Results — And How to Know Which
        One Is Right
      </h1>
      <p class="article__meta">April 7, 2026 · 5 min read</p>
    </header>

    <div class="article__body">
      <p>
        Someone posted to r/SchengenVisa recently in a quiet panic. They had
        entered the same travel dates into three different Schengen calculators
        and gotten back three different answers. The official European Commission
        tool said they had 69 days remaining. Two other popular sites said 15.
      </p>

      <p>They were considering cancelling their Christmas trip.</p>

      <p>
        The dates were the same. The results were 54 days apart. And they had no
        way of knowing which one was right.
      </p>

      <p>
        This is not unusual. In the same forum, another traveler described
        running their dates through several calculators and getting confusing
        results across all of them — before turning to ChatGPT as a tiebreaker.
        A third described cross-referencing two tools against each other just to
        feel more confident, not because either one had earned their trust.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Which calculator to trust</h2>

      <p>
        The short answer: use the{" "}
        <a
          href="https://ec.europa.eu/assets/home/visa-calculator/calculator.htm"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >official European Commission Schengen calculator</a
        >. It's maintained by the EU itself, uses the correct methodology, and
        is the authoritative reference. When results conflict, defer to it.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you need more than what it offers — tracking two people with
        different travel dates, saving your calculation, sharing a link with a
        partner, or planning future trips alongside confirmed past ones — that's
        what EuroVisaCalculator is built for. It uses the same methodology as
        the EU calculator, and we encourage you to run your dates through both
        and compare. If they disagree, we want to know.
      </p>

      <p>
        EuroVisaCalculator also has multi-country support on the roadmap, so as
        your travel extends beyond Schengen, the tool will grow with you.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Why calculators disagree in the first place</h2>

      <p>
        The Schengen rule itself is consistent. The disagreements come from two
        specific algorithmic choices that different tools make differently — and
        most tools don't tell you which choices they've made.
      </p>

      <h3>How the rolling window is applied</h3>

      <p>
        The 90/180 rule uses a rolling window, not a fixed period. On any given
        day, you look back exactly 180 days and count how many of those days you
        spent in Schengen. That total must never exceed 90.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some calculators don't implement it this way. Instead of a rolling
        window, they treat the 180 days as a fixed block with a defined start
        date. That's incorrect, and it produces dramatically different results
        for anyone with a complex travel history. The 54-day gap in the example
        above almost certainly comes from this — the EU calculator used the
        rolling window correctly; the others did not.
      </p>

      <h3>How entry and exit days are counted</h3>

      <p>
        The EU's official position is that both your entry day and your exit day
        count as full Schengen days, regardless of what time you cross the
        border. Not every calculator follows this. Some exclude one or both
        border days, treating a partial day as not counting. Over several trips,
        those small differences add up — easily 8 to 12 days across a year of
        frequent travel.
      </p>

      <p>
        These aren't bugs. They're algorithmic choices. The problem is that most
        tools don't document which choices they've made, so you can't evaluate
        the result you're being shown.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Why ChatGPT doesn't help</h2>

      <p>
        Using an AI chatbot as a tiebreaker is understandable — when two
        calculators disagree, a third opinion feels like progress. But language
        models don't do date arithmetic. They produce confident-sounding answers
        based on patterns in text, not actual calculation. For a rolling window
        across multiple trips, they're frequently wrong and have no way to flag
        their own uncertainty.
      </p>

      <p>A chatbot is not the right tool to verify a calculator result.</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>How to spot a calculator using the wrong methodology</h2>

      <p>
        Enter a single past trip of exactly 10 days and see how many days the
        tool counts. If it says 8 or 9, it's excluding border days — not the
        official methodology. If it says 10, it's counting correctly.
      </p>

      <p>
        The rolling window is harder to test without a complex travel history,
        but if you have trips spanning more than 180 days and two tools give
        results more than a few days apart, the one using a rolling window is
        right.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Christmas trip in that Reddit post was fine. The 69-day result from
        the EU calculator was correct. But that person had no way of knowing
        that without someone explaining why the tools disagreed — and that's not
        a problem anyone should have to solve mid-trip.
      </p>

      <hr />

